title: Mayo Clinic donates to La Crosse Warming Center to help bring comfort to those in need
text: LA CROSSE, Wis. (WEAU) - As the cold winter months are fast approaching, the La Crosse Warming Center is opening for the winter season. This year, they‚Äôre offering a little something extra for visitors, 45 reclining chairs. The chairs were donated by Mayo Clinic Health System. ‚ÄúWhen we shifted over to our new hospital, our old hospital rooms are just there without patients in them. The furniture in there we are looking to rehome to where it makes sense to organizations that serve the community,‚Äù says Mayo Clinic community engagement specialist Cindy Shireman. Catholic Charities, who runs the Warming Center, and Mayo Clinic have had a long-time relationship in La Crosse. ‚ÄúCatholic charities is a really good organization. The people that they‚Äôre serving deserve dignity, warmth, and hospitality. We‚Äôre happy that we can help in this way,‚Äù says Shireman. Catholic Charities advancement director Rob Grover says having the donated recliners is great because they were in a place where improvements were needed. ‚ÄúThe chairs we had were getting kind of older. They‚Äôre heavily used. It‚Äôs great to have these new chairs in here for our guests, folks that spend all day on the streets. For them to be able to come in and be in one of these comfortable chairs, being able to recline and sleep, we are so grateful to Mayo for making that happen,‚Äù says Grover. Grover adds that as the shelter opens up for the winter season, this donation will mean a lot for the people who come here. ‚ÄúFolks that are used to having nothing or having very little, to be able to come in here and sleep in a spot where the chair is nice and comfortable and newer and fresh, it also helps build dignity into our guests,‚Äù says Grover. Mayo Clinic officials say they plan to donate other equipment and furniture from the old hospital to other nonprofit organizations in the area soon. Copyright 2024 WEAU. All rights reserved.

title: Thousands of homes remain without power in wake of Storm Gerrit
text: Thousands of homes remain without power in wake of Storm Gerrit Thousands of homes remain without power as the post-storm cleanup begins in the wake of Storm Gerrit. Around 1,500 homes in Scotland experienced their second night without power in Scotland while a lightning strike hit supplies in Wales on Thursday. Power company Scottish and Southern Electricity Networks said it had restored supply to more than 46,000 properties that lost power due to the storm, with people in the north east and Shetland worst affected. ‚ö° We've now restored power to 46k customers [#stormgerrit]üè† 1.5k will be off overnight, we're giving help & advice.üë∑ Teams are working tonight to clear debris hindering access to faults.‚òï Full details of vans serving hot meals from 9am tomorrow are at [https://t.co/HSBcM400Fh] [pic.twitter.com/pnHIApyUvC] ‚Äî Scottish and Southern Electricity Networks (@ssencommunity) [December 28, 2023] They said the remaining homes should be reconnected on Friday with welfare vans serving hot food and drink to affected customers from 9am. Operations director Andy Smith said: ‚ÄúThis has been a difficult couple of days for the communities affected and I‚Äôm grateful to them for their patience and support as our teams work extremely hard to restore power.‚Äù National Grid UK said 36,000 properties were without power in Ceredigion on Thursday after lightning struck. Three men died after their 4√ó4 vehicle was submerged in the River Esk, near Glaisdale, on Thursday, North Yorkshire Police said. A supercell thunderstorm moved across the northwest of England on Thursday after a similar storm is thought to have resulted in a tornado that damaged homes in Greater Manchester on Wednesday. Around 100 properties were damaged by what police called a ‚Äúlocalised tornado‚Äù in Stalybridge, Tameside and in the badly-hit village of Carrbrook. Hayley McCaffer, 40, who lives in Carrbrook, told the PA news agency that some of her neighbours‚Äô houses ‚Äúare an absolute disaster‚Äù with missing roofs and ‚Äúsquished‚Äù cars. Damage will be covered by standard property insurance policies, the Association of British Insurers has said. ScotRail said many lines have been reopened but urged passengers to check for the latest information before travelling, a message echoed by LNER, Avanti West Coast and London Northwestern Railway who suspensed or cancelled services due to damage or system faults. Friday will see significant disruption for travellers wishing to travel on the London Euston and Watford Junction lines with services expected to be up and running by the end of the day. In Wales, the aftermath of the recent severe weather will see rail services hampered until Monday. üå¶Ô∏è Blustery showers are possible on Friday morning, with these most likely in the north and west. Many of us will also see some sunshine and some places may stay dry. üå¨Ô∏è Still windy in northern England and later Shetland, with gales possible, but otherwise somewhat less windy. [pic.twitter.com/hInP8LNF2c] ‚Äî Met Office (@metoffice) [December 28, 2023] Ferry services also experienced cancellations and delays due to storm activity with operator DFDS confirming sailings between Dover and France were delayed due to strong winds in the English Channel. Air travel in and out of the UK saw cancellations but most services have returned to normal. The Met Office reported the worst of Storm Gerrit had passed with the last few days of 2023 forecast to be unsettled with strong winds, rain and even snow on higher ground. Met Office chief forecaster Steven Ramsdale said: ‚ÄúHeavy rain will spread across all but the far north on Saturday, affecting similar areas previously affected by Storm Gerrit. However, this rainfall will be a step down from that seen during Storm Gerrit.‚Äù

title: Steam, √® addio su Chromebook: Google conferma ufficialmente
text:
Qualcuno non avrebbe mai voluto leggere un annuncio del genere ma a quanto pare √® ufficiale: ‚ÄúSteam for Chromebook Beta‚Äù terminer√† ufficialmente il 1¬∞ gennaio 2026. Non ci sar√† pi√π modo di usare tutti i giochi installati con questa famosa beta destinata solo ed esclusivamente ai dispositivi Chromebook.
Il progetto Steam per Chromebook
Lanciato nel 2022, Steam per Chromebook aveva suscitato curiosit√† tra gli appassionati di gaming, con Google che aveva cercato di portare un‚Äôesperienza di gioco PC su ChromeOS. Per farlo, l‚Äôazienda aveva collaborato con produttori di hardware per sviluppare dispositivi Chromebook pensati per il gaming. L‚Äôobiettivo era offrire giochi tramite Steam senza dover ricorrere a soluzioni di streaming, creando cos√¨ una possibilit√† di gioco nativa per un dispositivo generalmente utilizzato per produttivit√† e navigazione.
Un progetto che non ha preso piede
Nonostante l‚Äôentusiasmo iniziale, il programma √® rimasto in una fase beta per un lungo periodo, senza significativi progressi. L‚Äôassenza di aggiornamenti e l‚Äôinerzia del progetto avevano gi√† fatto intuire che questa fine sarebbe arrivata. Il ritiro di Steam su Chromebook ricorda un altro progetto di Google, Stadia, che dopo solo tre anni di vita √® stato chiuso nel 2023. Sebbene ChromeOS continuer√† a supportare il catalogo di giochi Android, ottimizzati per il sistema operativo, l‚Äôesperienza di gioco PC completa, promessa inizialmente da Steam su Chromebook, sta giungendo al termine.
Le alternative per il gaming su Chromebook
La fine del supporto Steam non segna la fine del gaming su Chromebook, ma semplicemente la fine di una fase sperimentale. Gli utenti che speravano di giocare a titoli pi√π complessi su Chromebook dovranno ora orientarsi verso soluzioni alternative. Tra queste ci sono il cloud gaming tramite servizi come GeForce Now e Xbox Cloud Gaming, o l‚Äôutilizzo di app Android ottimizzate per il sistema. Non √® stato annunciato un sostituto diretto del progetto, ma il gaming su Chromebook continuer√†, seppur in altre forme.
